Hi Das,

I&#39;d have at least the following tests:
- One or more tests for checking that the build up process works
correctly.
- One or more tests for every method which changes the state or
structure of your tree.

I&#39;m only guessing your navigation and inspection methods of TreeHolder
and TreeNode. Thus the resulting test class would look something like
this:

public class TreeHolderTest {
   private TreeHolder treeHolder;
   private TreeNode root;
   protected void setUp() {
	Collection coll = ...;
	treeHolder = new TreeHolder(coll);
	root = treeHolder.getRootNode();
   }
   public void testCreation() {
	assertTrue(!treeHolder.isEmpty)
	assertEquals(new TreeNode(&quot;....&quot;), root);
	assertEquals(3, root.getChildren().size());
	// navigate through the required tree and check the structure
   }
   public void testCalculateSomethig() {
	treeHolder.calculateSomething(...);
	// navigate to the nodes which should have changed 
	//and check their state
   }
   ...
}

The complex part is navigating and checking the state. If you have the
necessary public interface, try to extract duplicate code in your test
class into methods of its own, e.g.:
   private void assertNode(TreeNode node, String type, ...) {
	assertEquals(type, node.getType());
	....
   }

You might not have public methods for performing the navigation and
necessary checks. In that case you have several possibilities:
- Add those methods. When your tests need those methods the probability
is high that some other client code will need them soon.
- Implement a toString() in MyNode and/or TreeHolder which prints the
relevant attributes/structure and do a string compare.
- Use mock objects for testing your TreeHolder class. This would require
some major refactoring of your existing code.

The problem you are facing - that your code is hard to test - is mainly
due to your not having written the code test first. Code driven by
up-front tests is easy to test by definition. You have to get used to
doing it that way, though. I recommend the articles on objectmentor.com
and xprogramming.com as a starting point if you are interested in the
test first idea.

good luck,
Johannes

